SIMPLE: loiter
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Loiter
<hw>Loi"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Loitered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Loitering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[D.
<ets>leuteren</ets> to delay, loiter; cf; Prov. G. <ets>lottern</ets> to
be louse, <ets>lotter</ets> louse, slack, unsettled, vagrant, OHG.
<ets>lotar</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be slow in moving; to
delay; to linger; to be dilatory; to spend time idly; to saunter; to lag
behind.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sir John, you <qex>loiter</qex> here too long.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If we have <qex>loitered</qex>, let us quicken our pace.</q>
<rj><qau>Rogers.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To wander as an idle vagrant.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To linger; delay; lag; saunter; tarry.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Loiterer</ent>⟦br⟧
